00:31:47.590 --> 00:31:49.049
That's the only way.

00:31:49.049 --> 00:31:52.159
And the only way that law could be changed
in the state of California is to go back to

00:31:52.159 --> 00:31:53.159
the voters.

00:31:53.159 --> 00:31:54.799
If the voters wanted to change it.

00:31:54.799 --> 00:31:56.890
And I think that's virtually impossible.

00:31:56.890 --> 00:31:58.350
And then you mentioned Charlie Manson.

00:31:58.350 --> 00:32:01.230
So I do wanna tell you about Charlie Manson.

00:32:01.230 --> 00:32:04.779
Charlie Manson isn't on Death Row because
the US Supreme Court overturned the death

00:32:04.779 --> 00:32:05.919
penalty.

00:32:05.919 --> 00:32:09.669
And at that point in time when they did that,
life without possibility of parole was not

00:32:09.669 --> 00:32:12.120
a punishment available in California.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:14.940
It is now a punishment available in California.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:18.659
And no one gets out who is serving life without
possibility of parole unless they prove themself

00:32:18.659 --> 00:32:19.659
innocent.

00:32:19.659 --> 00:32:23.049
And we do have one individual, Obie Anthony,
who also works for Death Penalty Focus as

00:32:23.049 --> 00:32:28.490
a justice advocate, who was serving life without
possibility of parole and he was exonerated.

00:32:28.490 --> 00:32:30.500
Now he could have easily been on Death Row.

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:34.510
But the fact that he was serving life without
possibility of parole allowed him the opportunity

00:32:34.510 --> 00:32:36.379
to prove his innocence and he did.

00:32:36.379 --> 00:32:39.549
&gt;&gt;Natasha: And I'm really glad you brought
that up and asked that question.

00:32:39.549 --> 00:32:42.700
'cause I do think for a lot of people, that's
the core issue here.

00:32:42.700 --> 00:32:45.190
Is everyone wants to have safe families.

00:32:45.190 --> 00:32:50.600
And how do you guarantee that we're gonna
have safety in our communities in California.

00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:55.490
Just yesterday we had an event in Los Angeles
with victims and murder victim family members

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:57.279
who support the SAFE California Act.

00:32:57.279 --> 00:33:02.490
There are now over 400 murder victim family
members who have endorsed the initiative.

00:33:02.490 --> 00:33:05.779
One of the speakers yesterday is a woman named
Rose.

00:33:05.779 --> 00:33:10.910
Rose was raped when she was 22 years old by
a serial killer.

00:33:10.910 --> 00:33:14.460
The serial killer actually killed five women.

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:18.250
She is one of two women who survived his brutal
assault.

00:33:18.250 --> 00:33:24.030
And as a 22 year old woman, she knew she had
to do everything possible to make sure he

00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:26.600
never hurt another woman again.

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:30.850
And she actually testified against him in
three trials.

00:33:30.850 --> 00:33:33.480
Until he was sentenced to death twice.

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:37.809
That's how committed she was to making sure
that he would never hurt anyone.

00:33:37.809 --> 00:33:40.580
That was 28 years ago.

00:33:40.580 --> 00:33:42.299
He still sits on Death Row.

00:33:42.299 --> 00:33:45.429
And the appeals process continues.

00:33:45.429 --> 00:33:48.269
And Rose now supports the SAFE California
Act.

00:33:48.269 --> 00:33:54.210
Because she has realized that actually the
best way to ensure that he never hurts someone

00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:59.269
else again, and that California communities
are safe, is with life without possibility

00:33:59.269 --> 00:34:00.320
of parole.

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:04.299
She knows that if he is sentenced to life
without parole, he will never get out.

00:34:04.299 --> 00:34:07.030
He will actually be forced to work in prison.

00:34:07.030 --> 00:34:08.630
Which he doesn't now.

00:34:08.630 --> 00:34:12.010
He will pay into the victim's compensation
fund.

00:34:12.010 --> 00:34:15.370
And it will put an end to the appeals.

00:34:15.370 --> 00:34:18.330
Which have literally tortured her for 28 years.

00:34:18.330 --> 00:34:24.140
She has seen that in fact, the death penalty
is actually really just helping him.

00:34:24.140 --> 00:34:25.140
Because he has lawyers.

00:34:25.140 --> 00:34:28.610
And he has special privileges by being on
Death Row.

00:34:28.610 --> 00:34:30.990
And what she wants is to forget about him.

00:34:30.990 --> 00:34:36.980
What she wants is for the money that's being
spent on his case to go into things like violence

00:34:36.980 --> 00:34:38.800
prevention and treatment.

00:34:38.800 --> 00:34:40.910
So that people like him aren't made.

00:34:40.910 --> 00:34:42.290
Aren't created.

00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:44.470
Don't come to be in California anymore.

00:34:44.470 --> 00:34:45.920
She was just one of the speakers.

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:48.810
Another woman who was with us yesterday is
Nova Reeves.

00:34:48.810 --> 00:34:52.280
Her mother was killed by a serial killer in
Washington State.

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:54.280
She was 16 years old.

00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:56.540
For over ten years she didn't know.

00:34:56.540 --> 00:34:57.840
They didn't know where her mother was.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:34:58.840
They didn't know.

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:00.350
It took ten years to even solve the crime.

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:05.650
And the killer, that serial killer is serving
life without possibility of parole.

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:11.300
And she described how that for her, was a
moment that let her move on with her life.

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:12.800
This was sort of closure.

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:14.130
There will never be closure.

00:35:14.130 --> 00:35:17.480
You cannot close the hole in your heart.

00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:18.940
She'll never get her mother back.

00:35:18.940 --> 00:35:21.760
Rose will never get her youth back.

00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:25.480
But they can be freed from the criminal justice
system.

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:29.420
In a sense of life without parole guarantees
safety for the community.

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:32.560
It means dangerous people will never get out.

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:37.080
But it also lets us shift our resources to
what we really need to do.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:41.510
Which is actually catching more killers and
rapists who literally walk free right now.

00:35:41.510 --> 00:35:48.000
So this initiative is supported by victims
who have been through the worst possible experiences.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.070
Law enforcement who have seen the system firsthand.

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:55.300
As well as innocent people who know that we
can always make a mistake.

00:35:55.300 --> 00:35:57.510
&gt;&gt;Alan: Please, go ahead.

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:02.550
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Do you see any positive trends
in other states of overturning the death penalty.

00:36:02.550 --> 00:36:06.880
And why do you think this is, I mean I know
state's rights issues, but why isn't' it a

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:07.880
federal issue as well?

00:36:07.880 --> 00:36:10.450
&gt;&gt;Natasha: So I'll answer the second one first.

00:36:10.450 --> 00:36:13.980
And then I'm actually going to ask Randy and
Nate to describe their work in other states.

00:36:13.980 --> 00:36:18.000
So the death penalty is enacted state by state.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:21.580
Each state makes a decision about whether
they wanna have the death penalty on their

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:22.580
books.

00:36:22.580 --> 00:36:27.310
And as of now, we have 17 states that actually
have chosen to use life without parole instead

00:36:27.310 --> 00:36:28.810
of the death penalty.

00:36:28.810 --> 00:36:33.880
And it's not a federal issue in the sense
that you couldn't pass a federal law that

00:36:33.880 --> 00:36:37.680
would say to a state "You can't have the death
penalty."

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:40.890
That the states have the right to determine
their own criminal laws.

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:45.030
The only way the issue can be addressed on
a federal level of the entire country would

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:47.540
be through a US Supreme Court decision.

00:36:47.540 --> 00:36:51.170
As Jeannie mentioned, there was actually a
period where the US Supreme Court threw out

00:36:51.170 --> 00:36:53.330
the death penalty for the entire country.

00:36:53.330 --> 00:36:59.280
But then they allowed new death penalty laws
in 1976 that they thought were gonna fix the

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:00.280
problems.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:04.510
We know 34 years later that we have all the
same problems that we did before.

00:37:04.510 --> 00:37:09.520
It's clear that the Supreme Court will not
rule, not get rid of the death penalty across

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:14.760
the entire country until enough states on
their own have changed their laws.

00:37:14.760 --> 00:37:19.290
At a certain point the Supreme Court may say
"Enough states have done away with the death

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:21.560
penalty that the rest of the country has to."

00:37:21.560 --> 00:37:23.200
But we're not at that point yet.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:25.810
So I know that Randy and Nate have been really
active in other states.

00:37:25.810 --> 00:37:28.620
So maybe you could talk about the importance
of what's going on there.

00:37:28.620 --> 00:37:33.530
&gt;&gt;Randy: Well Witness to Innocence has worked
in the last five states that have abolished

00:37:33.530 --> 00:37:35.370
the death penalty.

00:37:35.370 --> 00:37:41.330
And I worked in New Mexico, Connecticut, Illinois,
and we've worked in Maryland.

00:37:41.330 --> 00:37:45.160
We've worked in Wisconsin to keep it from
coming back.

00:37:45.160 --> 00:37:49.590
And I believe that each state is different.

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:54.030
On their approach to why they should do away
with the death penalty.

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:57.850
Illinois, for example, was the mistakes that
they've made.

00:37:57.850 --> 00:37:59.690
They had to acknowledge it.

00:37:59.690 --> 00:38:04.500
There was 160 men on Death Row and 20 of us
were actually innocent.

00:38:04.500 --> 00:38:10.710
Now, you wouldn't get on an airplane if there
was 20 chances in 160 it was gonna crash.

00:38:10.710 --> 00:38:16.150
But yet, the death penalty had crashed years
before they put a moratorium in place.

00:38:16.150 --> 00:38:18.430
And years before they abolished it.

00:38:18.430 --> 00:38:22.230
And I think it's those mistakes and that cost.

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:24.670
Each state works on a different approach.

00:38:24.670 --> 00:38:29.590
And if you could educate the people about
the death penalty, the millions of dollars

00:38:29.590 --> 00:38:30.860
that they will save.

00:38:30.860 --> 00:38:32.310
Like California, for instance.

00:38:32.310 --> 00:38:34.380
It couldn't be any better example.

00:38:34.380 --> 00:38:36.170
28 years of appeals.

00:38:36.170 --> 00:38:43.460
Now, do you think capital qualified defense
lawyers and a prosecutors wanna see the death

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:44.460
penalty abolished?

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:45.840
No. you know why?

00:38:45.840 --> 00:38:47.710
It's a cash cow for 'em.

00:38:47.710 --> 00:38:53.180
It's nothing more than a stimulus package
that the tax payers are payin' the bill.

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:59.270
When you can give somebody life without parole,
and this is just my own personal opinion.

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:01.920
Because of being on Death Row.

00:39:01.920 --> 00:39:04.330
And then as opposed to life without parole.

00:39:04.330 --> 00:39:08.670
When you gotta deal with 1000 more violent.

00:39:08.670 --> 00:39:10.530
More hate, more rage.

00:39:10.530 --> 00:39:14.280
That there was times, had they rolled that
gurney by my cell, I'd have buckled myself

00:39:14.280 --> 00:39:16.690
on it.

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:22.610
Most people have no idea the horrors of maximum
security penitentiary life.

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:27.920
And to me, being executed would have been
early release.

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:29.620
It's a miserable existence.

00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:35.910
At least when you have life without parole,
you don't risk the possibility of executing

00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:37.080
an innocent person.

00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:39.930
Because you can release an innocent person
from prison.

00:39:39.930 --> 00:39:41.650
You can't release him from the grave.

00:39:41.650 --> 00:39:44.150
And Nate and I are perfect examples of that.

00:39:44.150 --> 00:39:45.280
&gt;&gt;Alan: Good.

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:51.760
&gt;&gt;Nathan: I wanna say something' on the first
