00:42:28.690 --> 00:42:32.570
But we believe that we know from the polling,
I can tell you, that the California voters

00:42:32.570 --> 00:42:33.900
support this initiative.

00:42:33.900 --> 00:42:37.590
A majority of California voters are on our
side.

00:42:37.590 --> 00:42:42.520
And so we are hopeful that with not as many
millions as you'll see in those other fights,

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:47.460
that we'll be able to get our message to the
key voters in California.

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:52.310
And really do view this as our moment when
we will win this initiative in California.

00:42:52.310 --> 00:42:56.520
&gt;&gt;Alan: So, I want to, go ahead.

00:42:56.520 --> 00:42:57.520
Come on.

00:42:57.520 --> 00:42:59.240
My goal is not to ask any questions.

00:42:59.240 --> 00:43:00.240
You know?

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:02.450
So if you guys don't do it then you're gonna
be forced with my questions.

00:43:02.450 --> 00:43:03.450
&gt;&gt;Male #1: I'll try to help you.

00:43:03.450 --> 00:43:04.450
Yeah.

00:43:04.450 --> 00:43:05.450
I just have a quick question.

00:43:05.450 --> 00:43:07.950
I'm wondering if the two gentlemen that were
on Death Row can go into a little bit more

00:43:07.950 --> 00:43:15.120
detail about what it's like for the experience
of being on Death Row, versus life in parole?

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:18.520
Because I think, financially it makes a lot
of sense to me.

00:43:18.520 --> 00:43:23.670
And I'm wondering what it's actually like
if you're accused, experientially, in prison.

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:25.190
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Well.

00:43:25.190 --> 00:43:32.960
[sighs] Death Row is, I mean, when you're
somewhere that you know you's not supposed

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:38.400
to be, for somethin' that you didn't do, you're
not comfortable at all.

00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:43.740
If you're in prison, doin' a life sentence,
and you there, you there because you supposed

00:43:43.740 --> 00:43:49.420
to be there for somethin' that you did, it's
a entirely different mentality.

00:43:49.420 --> 00:43:57.210
So Death Row, it creates this stress, it creates
tension, every single day that can really

00:43:57.210 --> 00:43:59.940
just cause your mind to just break in half.

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:01.230
So to speak.

00:44:01.230 --> 00:44:04.320
You get news from your daughter that she's
hurt.

00:44:04.320 --> 00:44:05.820
Or that her birthday is comin' up.

00:44:05.820 --> 00:44:07.750
And you can't attend.

00:44:07.750 --> 00:44:12.570
You get news like I did, that my mother had
died of a heart attack.

00:44:12.570 --> 00:44:16.960
Right in the middle of tryin' to hold my everything
together.

00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:18.630
It just totally different.

00:44:18.630 --> 00:44:19.630
And you're there.

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:20.630
On the yard.

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:22.180
With a friend.

00:44:22.180 --> 00:44:24.780
Who you met while you was on Death Row.

00:44:24.780 --> 00:44:26.830
Who's scheduled to be executed the next day.

00:44:26.830 --> 00:44:29.380
It is so different.

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:36.310
When you there, and you talkin' to a individual
who tomorrow, he's gonna be gone.

00:44:36.310 --> 00:44:39.530
I feel that's the difference right there.

00:44:39.530 --> 00:44:42.950
The pressure that comes with the death penalty.

00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:47.440
&gt;&gt;Natasha: Maybe I can ask Jeannie to jump
in on this too, since she's the most familiar

00:44:47.440 --> 00:44:50.050
with California's security systems.

00:44:50.050 --> 00:44:55.330
&gt;&gt;Jeannie: So Death Row in California is different
than Death Row was in Illinois.

00:44:55.330 --> 00:44:58.180
Because they were only allowed out of their
cell one hour a day.

00:44:58.180 --> 00:45:04.430
But in California, inmates who are on Death
Row are single celled, they're either in their

00:45:04.430 --> 00:45:09.360
cells watching TV or they're out on an exercise
yard.

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:12.910
Which they're allowed to go to seven days
a week for six hours a day.

00:45:12.910 --> 00:45:15.240
In California they have a legal team.

00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:17.050
For life.

00:45:17.050 --> 00:45:19.330
So they're, they receive a lot of visits.

00:45:19.330 --> 00:45:21.940
That legal team tends to take care of them.

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:22.970
Sends them packages.

00:45:22.970 --> 00:45:24.960
Christmas presents.

00:45:24.960 --> 00:45:27.120
Make sure they have newspapers.

00:45:27.120 --> 00:45:30.720
So they're really, they really depend on that
legal team.

00:45:30.720 --> 00:45:36.190
And they have visiting, what else did I forget?

00:45:36.190 --> 00:45:40.490
So, I will tell you, as the warden of San
Quentin I met every arriving, newly arrived

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:43.900
death row inmate in what we call classification.

00:45:43.900 --> 00:45:48.910
And I met at least 3 inmates who had asked
for the death penalty.

00:45:48.910 --> 00:45:53.710
Because they understood that Death Row was
an easier way of doing time in California

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:56.480
than serving the sentence of life without
possibility of parole.

00:45:56.480 --> 00:46:00.410
Because in this state, when you're serving
life without possibility of parole, you're

00:46:00.410 --> 00:46:02.090
in a maximum security prison.

00:46:02.090 --> 00:46:03.090
You're double-celled.

00:46:03.090 --> 00:46:05.270
You're expected to work.

00:46:05.270 --> 00:46:08.190
You're allowed to have visiting only two days
a week.

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:11.570
If there's enough room in the visiting room
for you to have visitors.

00:46:11.570 --> 00:46:13.840
Because there's a capacity on each of the
visiting rooms.

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:17.010
And often people will travel to prisons in
California and be turned away because the

00:46:17.010 --> 00:46:18.640
visiting room is full.

00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:23.830
So you can earn greater privileges if you
have life without possibility of parole, but

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:24.830
that is the difference.

00:46:24.830 --> 00:46:26.720
You have to earn those privileges.

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:30.160
On Death Row, those things are given to you
in the state of California.

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:34.170
That's why it's so much more expensive to
be on Death Row in terms of the housing of

00:46:34.170 --> 00:46:35.750
Death Row inmates.

00:46:35.750 --> 00:46:38.230
Because you're isolated from the general population.

00:46:38.230 --> 00:46:41.870
And either we're bringing the services to
you, or we're bringing you to the services.

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:45.750
So lot's of staff involved in all the processes
I just described.

00:46:45.750 --> 00:46:54.490
&gt;&gt;Alan: So, one thing that I think has, uh,
focused the issue more than any other thing

00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:59.100
in the last 10 or 15 years, is DNA.

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:00.320
And DNA analysis.

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:04.490
And the technology that has changed.

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:11.740
Which offers potentially irrefutable proof
of innocence.

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:14.560
And has cut through some of the layers of
bureaucracy.

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:17.790
So, you wanna talk a little bit about the
technology changes?

00:47:17.790 --> 00:47:21.960
Since we're, there's a room, with a lot of
technologists involved.

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:22.960
&gt;&gt;Natasha: Absolutely.

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:26.920
So DNA is probably what's captured people's
attention and brought the issue of innocence

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:29.990
to the public in a way that few things have.

00:47:29.990 --> 00:47:31.650
I'll let Jeannie actually address this.

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:35.310
'cause she talks about how much law enforcement
has learned from DNA.

00:47:35.310 --> 00:47:39.880
But what's interesting is these two men, didn't
say the words DNA when they explained to you

00:47:39.880 --> 00:47:41.750
how they were proven innocent.

00:47:41.750 --> 00:47:45.240
In fact, their cases didn't involve DNA evidence.

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:47.150
&gt;&gt;Alan: Or any physical evidence at all.

00:47:47.150 --> 00:47:48.150
&gt;&gt;Natasha: or any physical evidence.

00:47:48.150 --> 00:47:51.390
So that's the thing, when there's no physical
evidence, it also means there's no physical

00:47:51.390 --> 00:47:53.120
evidence to prove that you're innocent.

00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:59.450
So in fact, DNA evidence is available in only
about 15 percent of homicide cases.

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:04.360
And in those cases, you can have that tool
available to tell you if this is the right

00:48:04.360 --> 00:48:05.360
person or not.

00:48:05.360 --> 00:48:07.790
But in fact, the majority of cases there are
no witnesses.

00:48:07.790 --> 00:48:09.690
There is no DNA.

00:48:09.690 --> 00:48:13.010
And the kinds of mistakes we heard about continue
to happen.

00:48:13.010 --> 00:48:17.670
So while DNA is an incredible tool that has
been very helpful in showing us that we make

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:21.610
mistakes, it isn't the silver bullet that's
gonna make sure that we never make mistakes.

00:48:21.610 --> 00:48:24.060
But I think Jeannie's perspective is also
helpful in this.

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:27.810
&gt;&gt;Jeannie: Well, what I say about DNA is that
DNA has taught us in law enforcement not to

00:48:27.810 --> 00:48:29.280
believe everything we think.

00:48:29.280 --> 00:48:35.330
Through DNA we found out that eyewitness testimony
is wrong more often than it's right.

00:48:35.330 --> 00:48:40.460
We found out that people falsely confess to
crimes.

00:48:40.460 --> 00:48:45.120
And we found out, which I think we all, we
knew all along, we just didn't wanna admit

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:49.920
we knew it, is that jailhouse snitches lie
most of the time.

00:48:49.920 --> 00:48:55.520
And it's because of DNA that we have the growing
number of exonerees in the state of California

00:48:55.520 --> 00:48:57.360
and around the country.

00:48:57.360 --> 00:49:01.600
Because it's not, because courts and others
are not only questioning those cases where

00:49:01.600 --> 00:49:05.690
DNA is available, but because of what we've
learned from DNA is opening the doors to other

00:49:05.690 --> 00:49:07.440
issues where DNA is not available.

00:49:07.440 --> 00:49:10.500
And people are taking a much more careful
look.

00:49:10.500 --> 00:49:14.830
But, DNA is not the answer to this issue.

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:17.260
Replacing the death penalty is the answer.

00:49:17.260 --> 00:49:20.520
&gt;&gt;Randy: I would like to say that DNA is fabulous.

00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:22.380
It's a great safety net.

00:49:22.380 --> 00:49:23.910
But it's such a small one.

00:49:23.910 --> 00:49:30.450
When you have other evidence that the prosecutors
use like eyewitness testimony.

00:49:30.450 --> 00:49:37.840
Why is it so hard for people to believe that
a jailhouse snitch, or a supposed eyewitness

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:45.890
to a murder, won't get up there on that stand,
for the prosecution, and lie?

00:49:45.890 --> 00:49:51.790
They do it every day in our courts across
this country.

00:49:51.790 --> 00:49:56.250
Many many crimes are committed right in the
courtroom every day in this country.

00:49:56.250 --> 00:50:01.230
Because of prosecutors with their absolute
immunity and their qualified immunity clauses

00:50:01.230 --> 00:50:02.480
that they have.

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:05.630
They can suborn perjury.

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:08.140
They can fabricate evidence.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:10.120
They can hide evidence.

00:50:10.120 --> 00:50:13.840
And all of this is what leads to wrongful
convictions.

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:19.440
You cannot have an irreversible punishment
in place when prosecutors have that kind of

00:50:19.440 --> 00:50:24.040
power and are absolutely immune.

00:50:24.040 --> 00:50:28.320
&gt;&gt;Alan: So we only have a few minutes here
left.

00:50:28.320 --> 00:50:32.560
I want to focus on one particular piece of
your story.

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:34.810
If I can.

00:50:34.810 --> 00:50:39.820
Which is, the moment that you found out that
you were gonna get released.

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:46.610
Or that you know, when you got the word that
after all these years and all the suffering

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:50.620
and all this pain, you know, how did it happen?

00:50:50.620 --> 00:50:52.280
And what did you feel?

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:54.270
And what happened from that?

00:50:54.270 --> 00:50:58.010
From that moment on to the moment you're reunited
from your family.

00:50:58.010 --> 00:50:59.010
What happened?

00:50:59.010 --> 00:51:03.340
&gt;&gt;Randy: Well, it was after, it was almost
16 years.

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:06.360
As I said, I'd lost every state appeal.

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:12.500
When I found out that my federal habeas corpus
opinion had come down that morning, but they

00:51:12.500 --> 00:51:13.970
didn't know the results.

00:51:13.970 --> 00:51:15.430
&gt;&gt;Alan: How did you get that news.

00:51:15.430 --> 00:51:16.430
Who talked--?

00:51:16.430 --> 00:51:19.970
&gt;&gt;Randy: My attorneys called me from out of
my cell.

00:51:19.970 --> 00:51:24.160
And I knew it was either gonna be bad news
or it was gonna be good news.

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:27.300
And I set down in the captains office.

00:51:27.300 --> 00:51:28.300
And he handed me the phone.

00:51:28.300 --> 00:51:33.880
And she says, my attorney says "Randy, are
you settin' down?" and I said "Yes."

00:51:33.880 --> 00:51:39.460
And says "Judge McCaskey had just granted
all 17 issues in your federal habeas corpus

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:40.460
position.

00:51:40.460 --> 00:51:45.430
And ordered the state of Illinois to either
retry you or release you in 120 days."

00:51:45.430 --> 00:51:46.960
I'm sitting there.

00:51:46.960 --> 00:51:50.640
And I asked her, I said "Can you repeat that
for me please?"

00:51:50.640 --> 00:51:51.640
[laughter]

00:51:51.640 --> 00:51:56.740
Because that was the first bit of good news
that I had had in almost 17 years.

00:51:56.740 --> 00:51:58.210
But it was shock.

00:51:58.210 --> 00:52:04.280
It was just as shocking as the moment the
jury opened their mouth and convicted me of

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:05.760
this crime.

00:52:05.760 --> 00:52:12.520
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Uh, as for me, I was released on
bond first.

00:52:12.520 --> 00:52:19.291
After I got the new trial, the prosecutors
told the Illinois Supreme Court that they

00:52:19.291 --> 00:52:22.400
could not retry me because there is no case.

00:52:22.400 --> 00:52:26.610
If they upheld my new trial, there's no case.

00:52:26.610 --> 00:52:29.020
So when I came back for the new trial.

00:52:29.020 --> 00:52:32.020
I was thinkin' they was just gonna let me
go.

00:52:32.020 --> 00:52:34.520
Soon as I went before the judge.

00:52:34.520 --> 00:52:39.410
But the prosecutor said, "We're not bound
by what the prosecutor said to the Supreme

00:52:39.410 --> 00:52:40.410
Court."

00:52:40.410 --> 00:52:42.490
And they said they was gonna retry me.

00:52:42.490 --> 00:52:45.570
And they set my bond at a million dollars.

00:52:45.570 --> 00:52:51.990
So, Governor Ryan, the governor of Illinois
at the time, he emptied out Death Row by giving

00:52:51.990 --> 00:52:55.010
all the prisoners on Death Row a pardon.

00:52:55.010 --> 00:53:00.080
When he done that, one of my best friends,
Aaron Patterson came home.

00:53:00.080 --> 00:53:02.200
He was completely exonerated.

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:08.960
He got his state compensation pay and he put
up 100,000 dollars and came and bond me out.

00:53:08.960 --> 00:53:14.020
We had made a pact while we was on Death Row,
that whichever one of us get out first would

00:53:14.020 --> 00:53:16.570
reach back and get the other.

00:53:16.570 --> 00:53:22.560
When the guards came to my cell, and told
me "Pack up, you goin' home."

00:53:22.560 --> 00:53:24.950
I really thought he was jokin'.

00:53:24.950 --> 00:53:27.430
And but I started packin' up.

00:53:27.430 --> 00:53:31.990
But I don't know why I was thinkin' he was
jokin'.

00:53:31.990 --> 00:53:33.060
But it was real.

00:53:33.060 --> 00:53:34.670
I packed my things up.

00:53:34.670 --> 00:53:35.840
And I went to downstairs.

00:53:35.840 --> 00:53:38.510
And they processed me out.

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:42.900
And when I got to the last gate, I had a folder
with me.

00:53:42.900 --> 00:53:44.980
And I told the guard, "What next."

00:53:44.980 --> 00:53:47.570
He said "Just walk out that door."

00:53:47.570 --> 00:53:50.000
I said "Just walk out?"

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:51.460
He said "Yeah."

00:53:51.460 --> 00:53:54.250
And so I walked out the door.

00:53:54.250 --> 00:53:57.630
And as I was walking, I smelled somethin'.

00:53:57.630 --> 00:53:59.980
That I hadn't smelled.

00:53:59.980 --> 00:54:02.770
And when I looked up, it was a tree.

00:54:02.770 --> 00:54:06.440
It was a tree high in the air over my head.

00:54:06.440 --> 00:54:09.990
And I almost fell right on my face right then
on the ground.

00:54:09.990 --> 00:54:12.430
I had to catch my balance.

00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:14.310
I thought about what made me do that.

00:54:14.310 --> 00:54:20.640
And there was the fact that I hadn't been
under a tree in 18 years.

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:24.530
And it threw me off.

00:54:24.530 --> 00:54:26.020
But then, I walked on out.

00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:27.260
And all my family.

00:54:27.260 --> 00:54:28.660
The press.

00:54:28.660 --> 00:54:29.660
It was beautiful.

00:54:29.660 --> 00:54:32.040
&gt;&gt;Alan: Well great.

00:54:32.040 --> 00:54:37.860
So I can't imagine another way, a better way
to end today than that story.

00:54:37.860 --> 00:54:39.600
I wanna thank everyone for being here.

00:54:39.600 --> 00:54:47.170
I think it's really been a, I feel like the
education that we get from hearing the stories

00:54:47.170 --> 00:54:49.700
of people that are inside the system.

00:54:49.700 --> 00:54:53.670
And understand that it's just so different
than we sometimes see.

00:54:53.670 --> 00:54:54.670
You know.

00:54:54.670 --> 00:54:55.670
In the media and on the television.

00:54:55.670 --> 00:54:56.670
And other things.

00:54:56.670 --> 00:54:59.550
And I just wanna thank you very much for bringing
your stories.

00:54:59.550 --> 00:55:00.880
You know, to Google.

00:55:00.880 --> 00:55:05.470
And to the people that will watch the video.

00:55:05.470 --> 00:55:07.110
Because I think it's a very important issue.

00:55:07.110 --> 00:55:12.710
And I think your perspectives are incredibly
important to get the word out.

00:55:12.710 --> 00:55:17.220
And changes that we as citizens of California
can potentially make.

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:21.820
And I think the other thing that's important
is that California's kind of a bell ringer

00:55:21.820 --> 00:55:23.510
for the rest of the world.

00:55:23.510 --> 00:55:26.070
And for the United States in general.

00:55:26.070 --> 00:55:32.030
That if California goes, if California changes
its law.

00:55:32.030 --> 00:55:37.610
If we go with life without parole, there's
a very good chance that the rest of the nation

00:55:37.610 --> 00:55:39.130
will follow us.

00:55:39.130 --> 00:55:42.310
And I think the stakes are very high.

00:55:42.310 --> 00:55:49.540
And I appreciate the time that each of you
has spent with this issue and Natasha for

00:55:49.540 --> 00:55:51.130
leading this effort.

00:55:51.130 --> 00:55:52.800
And I wish you the very best of luck.

00:55:52.800 --> 00:55:53.800
So thank you everybody.

00:55:53.800 --> 00:55:53.801
[applause]

